review_blob:
Drink at room temp for a fine well hopped and candied IPA, Drink cool for
a great session beer. Perfect IPA identical to the 90 min but much easier to
drink. Great for the summer.

Malty and Hoppy with some burnt sugars and burning alcohols. Great tasting but i felt the carbonation like a soda pop, artificial like.
Its also got a funky finish to it.

beer_brewer_name: Hair of the Dog Brewing Company
review_blob: Wow this is by far the best Barley Wine out there. Zero soapiness and no flowery scents. Most BW are cough syrupy. This is a more hopped up version and the sweetness comes in the form of brown sugar and thick malts. The hops are not bittering but definetly present. A bit on the sweet side but its a great desert beer.
beer_name: Hair of the Dog Doggie Claws (2003-)

review_blob: A very malty and strongly hopped bareleywine. Not syrupy and cloying like most. Pretty easy drinking with a good warming alcohol kick.
A regular tasting brown ale with a good amount of hops to make it intresting. Very good brew for a burger.
beer_name: Bear Republic Peter Brown Tribute Ale

review_blob: This is more of a Vanilla Stout. Aroma is milk and coffee with loads of vanilla. Taste is the same with some milk chocolate and roasted coffee beans. Palate is super sweet but not cloying. Slightly carbonated but enough to offset the sweetness.
beer_name: Southern Tier Jah-va Imperial Coffee Stout

review_blob: Like a champagne beer, its imposible to open or pour without the foam spilling over. Very smooth and silky carbonation though, Flavors are citrusy and lightly hoppy. The aroma is bandaid and soap. The finish however is bready and earthy with a typical Carolus Green apple hint to it. Alcohol not noticeable.
It tasted more like a sour ale to me, with some funkiness and spiced up with cinamon and chocolate. Very yeasty and lactic, great palate. Finishes a bit too sweet though with some woody overtones.

I got a lot of flowery and soapy flavors, probably from the hops. I was hopping to get more caramelly flavors and some roastiness. Its spiced up and has tu much hops for the style. Its a bit watery too.
beer_name: Alpine Beer Company McIlhenneys Irish Red

review_blob: Starts off with a harsh hop bite, then eases off to a milder IIPA. With a one sided feel to it. If what you want is a hop pellet with liittle else this is it. For me it lacked the malt balance and a little more flavor complexity. It does finish with a nice tropical fruitiness and a bit on the sweet side.
Average pale ale, No disernable honey accents, hoppy bitterness thruout and bisquity. Finishes crisp and hoppy.
Watery and bland like a bud , but it has a more real taste. Maybe its the marketing but i tasted more hops and a fresher crisper beer.
beer_name: Green Valley Brewing Stone Mill Pale Ale

beer_brewer_name: Hair of the Dog Brewing Company
review_blob:
Very hazy and almost muddy looking. I got a green apple with caramel and covered with hop pellets. Very smooth and milky palate with some sweetness.
Nice and low alcohol keeps the flavors very present. Resiny aftertaste with lots of earthy tones.
beer_name: Hair of the Dog Blue Dot Double IPA

beer_brewer_name: Hair of the Dog Brewing Company
review_blob:
Its says ";GOLDEN ALE";, and it says ";made in the Belgium tradition";. And now i see its a barleywine. It doesnt really know what it is.
Pours flat with a nice fruity and vanilla nose. Tastes sugary, with cherries, plums and oranges. Palate is super sweet with a big alcohol burn. Finish is herbal and spicey with more alcohol.

I thought it was pretty honest to its style.. Although not that red, it did have a malty, earthy and slightly caramely nose and taste. Some grassy hops and bitterness in the finish. Crisp and refreshing with some nice flavor.

Smells sweet and yeasty with the typical Candi.
 Expecting sweetness in the flavor but found almost none, this ale is nicely dry with some yeastiness and a citrusy biterness that is not too harsh but noticeable. A very slight funk in the finish.

Wow one of the best ambers ive had.. except it not actually an amber. Its more of a light imperial red or a malty ipa.
Anyway full of malts and full of hops, caramely but bitter, floral but sweet, piney and chocolaty. In a style of its own... i wasnt expecting such a good brew. Finishes fruity with a nice hop kick.

Deep black with a tiny dark brown-purpulish head. This this is a milk shake! Easily the thickist beer ive had ever.  Very elegant brew (once in the glass). Nice complexity of dark fruits, chocolate and smoke. Lots of coffee too with a nice bitter finish.
I like this style a lot! Its an amber beer on steroids. Creamy texture and lots of roasted mixed malts. Caramely, a bit of milk chocolate and some fruitiness at the end. Id love to try this on tap.
Sweet and smokey aromas, for me it smelled better than it tasted, Flavor was one dimensional.. all smoke and roasted malts. Pretty dry finish and no nutttyness to be found anywhere.
Kinda soda pop like. With a semi-real, semi-artificial taste to it. Some caramel and roastiness to it. Refreshing, but nothing much to it i guess.

130 IBUs ?? Where was that? This is the smoothest IIPA ive ever tased, The hops and bitterness are there, but mixed with the candy sugar, you get a whole new taste. This Belgium Imperial IPA should be a style on its own. To me it its grossly underrated.Except that its a tad too sweet.. which drowns out the hop bitterness, its pretty much a perfect brew, for me. It tastes so elegant and smooth it shouldnt even be called beer.

Dark brown, completly opaque, with a small head, no lacing.  Wooden bench and coffee aroma. Taste is White wine, fresh cut wood, coffee and toffee. Palate is med. bodied, fresh, powdery. Finishes with an aspirin, toffee bitterness, and leaves a dry tongue aftertaste. 
Very intresting.. new flavors, new complexities. Should pair well with very specific foods.

I guess this was the best beer i had at Clybornes. Rich and caramely with notes of roasted malts, honey and some vanilla too. A faint aftertaste of milk chocolate and hops. Pretty tastey and paired well with the food.

Yuk... served extra cold at Clybornes. Overwhelmning tastes of burnt plastic and asprin. Worst porter ive had by far. Left almost all of it. Waitress didnt care, she still billed me for it, even when i told her it was probably oxidized.

Draft at Clyborne. 
A regular belgian ale, a bit lighter in flavor than the originals. More citrus fruits than others. Some hop in there too.
Also the regular banana, buble gum and spices but a bit watered down.
Maybe it was served way to cold.

I used to feel the same way about I.Stouts. Youll get the palate someday CarterHayes.
One of the best imperials ive had, perfect palate, smooth and velvety. Flavors of bourbon, oak, vanilla and roasted walnuts. 
Aftertaste of nuts and molases, with a nice bitter-sweetness to it.
A very sweet and easy drinking barley wine, tasted of caramel, butterscotch and a bit of raisins. Hoppy aftertaste with a bit of anise too. Nice head and retention. No alcohol burn or tastes at all.
Redishh black, no head. What little taste it had was of caramel malts and very lightly hopped. For a Dark Ale its was pretty watery and insipid, now that its rated as a vienna, maybe it was ok.

I like the low alcohol on this IIPA. It had a nice hop combo with a light malt integration. Tastes of resin and pine mixed with citrus and caramel. Finishes a tad fruity and astringent. Palate is smooth for its kind.

Very hoppy and piney for what i was expecting, its says amber ale but its listed as a Bitter? I dont get it..  neither did i get the  taste. A mix of an IPA with some amber ale and spices. I got an ethery aftertaste with some yeast mixed in. Strange beer.

beer_brewer_name: Hair of the Dog Brewing Company
review_blob: A very fruity blonde ale with notes of rasberries, blood orange and a bit of champagne. Scents of hops all over with a citrusy ending and then some more hops with honey.. Very complex and refreshing at the same time.. Intresting.

The most impresive palate ive felt in a beer. Tastes of oatmeal, wiskey, wood and roasted malts, honey and sweet chocolate with a dry finish of lingering hops (or sour grapes?) and a bit of smokeiness too.
Very niicely done.

beer_brewer_name: Hair of the Dog Brewing Company
review_blob:
Thanks South Bay! I hope they keep selling it there forever. Amazing dark rich palate with huge froth. Smoke, Plum, dark brown sugar, roasted almonds and chocolate. Finish has the lightest hop biterness, vanilla and wood.
MMM great!!!
Wow i was expecting a blond, and i got an amber brew with lots of yeasty fruity flavors with some honey and roasted wheat. A little sweetnes with a very mild hop precence.

Brought by my parents trip to Belgium. Not the bliss i was expecting. A slightly watery palate, very dry but with sweet aromas of chocolate, beets and licorice. A bit astringent too with a carton taste to it.

One dimensional hop precence... needs some variety or pairing with some fruity flavors. More hops than malts, nice hazy orange color with beige lasting head. A tad watery for its kind, very astringent and bitter... needs a bit of a sweet kick to balance out. But it does what its names says "hop juice" thats about it.

Wow i thought this was an imp. stout.
Tons of flavor.. no licorice though. Chocolate mostly with coffee and molases. Slightly bitter and a long finish. 
A bit of a band aid aftertaste.

This is very difrent than the bottled version which is an Imperial Red, this amber red is smooth and caramely with a nice hop precence. Its light and well carbonated. For me its the best pairing brew to there great pies.
beer_name: Pizza Port Shark Bite Red Ale

review_blob:
Smells of roasted malts, toasted bread, caramel and fruits.
Looks Clear pale brown with disapating head.
Tastes as it smells except with rasberry syrup and coke a cola.
Feels very light and watery and has cabonation like a soda pop.
Could use more body and authentic rasberry flavor.
Very mild, waterd down... Not what i was expecting from a Belgian Brewer. Some caramel and spices... a tad smoked. Not bad flavor, just not enough of it. Looks better than it tastes.

Starts metalic, aluminum and vegetables.. begins getting better while it warms.. molases, bittering hops and a bit of breadyness. And ends much better with tons of caramel, bananas, toffee and a med. body.

Sweet flavors all around of almonds, apples and yeast. Hints of brown sugar, sour milk and dark berries. A bit of oak and honey too.
The sourness is not to pungeant and it is melowed buy a fair amount sweetness.
Very easy sour to drink.
Bready and bisquity with lots of honey sweetness and a citric hop taste in the finish.  Fruity aftertaste... lots of flavor for a pale ale.

beer_brewer_name: Port Brewing Co / The Lost Abbey
review_blob:
These double Reds should be in a catagory of there own now. My favorite style Imperial Red Ales. 
Delicious, chewey, super malty with a strong hop precence. Toffe and nutty aftertastes with a slight lemony hint.
Unoticable alcohol.
beer_name: Port Brewing Shark Attack Double Red Ale

review_blob: Its a guiness with less body and more sweet milk chocolate. Pours brown with a med head. Taste is autentic and though a bit to sweet is still pretty good and drinkable.
Ive never had a great Kolsh and this is no exception. Prety bland beer with a watery body and no head retention. There was however a nice buisquity taste to it with a mild amount of hops.
beer_name: Flying Dog Tire Bite Golden Ale

review_blob: More of an Iipa with tons of hops, a high alcohol profile and a decent malt background. Tastes of Pine needles, flowers and fruits. Full bodied with a sweet subtle finish.
beer_name: Flying Dog Double Dog Double Pale Ale

review_blob: I guess i got a bad one. Mine had a strong taste of sour milk, and was very yeasty. I hope to rerate again soon.

Had it at the Santa Fe shopping mall in Mexico city. I felt a very artificial taste in this, watered down with a caramel and smokey taste. Its better than other Mexican Viennas but maybe i dont like the style too much. I dont know why there are so many viennas in Mexico.
